{"cursor":"7929","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox scientist |name = Ernst Heinrich Weber |image = Ernst Heinrich\nWeber.jpg |image_size = 150px |caption = Ernst Heinrich Weber |birth_date = June\n24, 1795 |birth_place = Wittenberg, Saxony, Holy Roman Empire |death_date =\nJanuary 26, 1878 |death_place = Leipzig, Saxony |residence = |citizenship =\n|nationality = German |ethnicity = |field = physician |work_institutions =\n|alma_mater = |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = experimental\npsychology |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced =\n|prizes = |religion = |footnotes = |signature = }} 'Ernst Heinrich Weber' (June\n24, 1795 – January 26, 1878) was a German physician who is considered one\nof the founders of experimental psychology.\n\nWeber studied medicine at Wittenberg University. In 1818 he was appointed\nAssociate Professor of comparative anatomy at Leipzig University, where he was\nmade a Fellow Professor of anatomy and physiology in 1821. Kruta, V. (1976)\nWeber, Ernst Heinrich. In C.C.Gillespie (Ed) Dictionary of Scientific Biography,\nVol. XIV, pp. 199-202. New York: Charles Scribner's Sons.\n\nIn the 1820s or 1830s Weber began studying the tactile senses, the two-point\nthreshold and weight perception. He published his early work in 1834 in Latin\n(De Tactu), Weber, E.H. (1834)De pulsu, resorptione, auditu et tactu.\nAnatationes anatomicae et physiologicae. Leipzig: Koehler. and published\nthis together with later work in 1846 in German (Tastsinn und\nGemeingefÃ¼hl). Weber, E.H. (1846) Tastsinn und GemeingefÃ¼hl. In R. Wagner\n(Ed) HandwÃ¶rterbuch der Physiologie. Vol. III, pp. 481-588. Brunswick:\nVieweg. Ross, H. E. and Murray, D.J. (Eds & Transl)(1996)E.H. Weber on\nthe tactile senses (2nd edition). Hove: Erlbaum (UK) Taylor & Francis. He\nfound that weight discrimination was much finer with active lifting than when\nthe weights were placed on supported hands. He also found that the just-\nnoticeable difference (jnd) of the change in the magnitude of a stimulus (viz.,\nsmall weights held in the hand) is proportional to the magnitude of the stimulus\n(e.g., 5%), rather than being an absolute value (e.g., 5 grams). Gustav\nFechner named this Weber's Law. Fechner explored this relation further in the\n1850s and, integrating over Weber's proportional jnds, argued for a logarithmic\nrelation between physical and psychological (or perceived) magnitudes. This new\nlaw became known as Fechner's Law, or the Weber-Fechner Law, and formed the\nbasis of Fechner's new science of psychophysics.\n\nWeber is also noted for his discoveries in anatomy, in particular that of the\nexistence of a rudimentary uterus in male mammals, but his greater fame rests\nupon his pioneer work in the exploration of the sense organs. His work upon the\near and upon the cutaneous senses â pressure, temperature, and what was then\ncalled the âcommon senseâ â led to the introduction of the experimental method\nin psychology. The important law which usually bears his name was the first\ngeneral law in psychophysics. However, Weber himself produced very\nlittle experimental data on the topic, and later work showed that the law holds\nonly approximately in the mid range for most sense modalities. Laming, D.\n(1986) Sensory analysis. New York: Academic Press Weber did not propose\nany theoretical reason behind the law. He would be better remembered for his\nwork on the relation between neural structure and sensation. Ross, H.E.\n(1995) Weber then and now. Perception, 24: 599-602.\n\nIn 1866 Weber retired as professor of physiology and also as professor of\nanatomy in 1871. Around this time he and his brother, Eduard Friedrich Weber,\ndiscovered the inhibitory power of the vagus nerve.\n","linknr":328,"url":"Ernst_Heinrich_Weber","recorded":1376420976,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Ernst_Heinrich_Weber&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Ernst_Heinrich_Weber&action=edit","//bit